Title: The Jungle Book
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Rudyard Kipling's story collection (1894, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026

====

FADE IN:

EXT. SEEONEE HILLS - WOLF DEN - NIGHT

FATHER WOLF stirs in the mouth of his cave as SHERE KHAN, a massive tiger with a lame foot, prowls too near.

MOTHER WOLF
(low growl)
Shere Khan honors us. What does he want?

SHERE KHAN (O.S.)
(from the brush)
A man's cub went this way. Its parents ran. Give it to me.

A small, brown, naked HUMAN INFANT crawls into the den, entirely unafraid, and pushes in among the wolf cubs to nurse.

FATHER WOLF
(to Shere Khan)
The cub is ours -- to kill when we choose, not at the bidding of any striped cattle-killer.

Shere Khan snarls and retreats, thwarted by the Wolf Pack Law.

MOTHER WOLF
(cradling the cub)
He shall run with the Pack. We will call him Mowgli, the Frog.

CUT TO:

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT (YEARS LATER)

MOWGLI (10, feral, quick, at home among animals) stands before AKELA, the great Lone Wolf who leads the Pack, and the assembled wolves. BALOO the bear and BAGHEERA the black panther stand as his sponsors.

AKELA
Man-cubs are not spoken for lightly. Who speaks for this cub?

BALOO
(gruff, fond)
I speak for the man-cub. I will teach him myself.

BAGHEERA
(smooth, watchful)
And I will pay the price for him -- a fat bull, newly killed, if the Pack will take him in according to the Law.

The wolves accept. Only SHERE KHAN's low growl carries across the clearing.

SHERE KHAN
The cub is mine in the end. Wolves, he will be man among men, and you will thank me for his death when that day comes.

AKELA
(steady)
Go to your lair, lame one. The Man-cub is Pack now.

CUT TO:

EXT. JUNGLE CLEARING - DAY (LATER)

Baloo teaches Mowgli the Law of the Jungle -- word by word, patiently, occasionally cuffing him for inattention.

BALOO
Say it again, and mind the Master Words.

MOWGLI
(reciting, half-bored)
"For the strength of the Pack is the Wolf, and the strength of the Wolf is the Pack."

BALOO
Good. Now -- the words that will buy you mercy from the People of the Air, the People of the Water, and the Hunting People.

Suddenly, hands seize Mowgli from above -- the BANDAR-LOG, the mischievous Monkey-People, swarm down and carry him screaming into the treetops.

CUT TO:

EXT. COLD LAIRS - RUINED CITY - DAY

The monkeys parade Mowgli through crumbling temples, delighted with their new toy. Baloo and Bagheera race below, unable to climb fast enough. Bagheera sends a desperate call skyward.

BAGHEERA
(shouting up)
Chil! Chil the Kite! Carry word to Kaa!

CUT TO:

EXT. COLD LAIRS - RUINED FOUNTAIN - CONTINUOUS

KAA, an enormous rock python, glides into the ruins, drawn by the chaos. The monkeys scatter in terror at the mere sight of him.

Bagheera and Baloo burst in moments later, exhausted and battered, to find Mowgli unharmed, sitting calmly beside the great snake.

BALOO
(relieved, gruff)
Little Frog, you gave us a fright.

KAA
(coiling, amused)
The manling has manners. He greeted me by the correct name.

Bagheera, still catching his breath, bows respectfully to Kaa, who begins his slow, swaying Hunger Dance -- the monkeys, entranced, edge closer despite themselves.

BAGHEERA
(quickly, to Mowgli)
Do not look at his eyes, Little Brother. Come away now, while you still remember how to want to.

They slip away as Kaa's dance closes in on the last of the transfixed monkeys.

CUT TO:

EXT. JUNGLE - WATERING PLACE - DAY (LATER, DRY SEASON)

A drought grips the jungle. Under the Water Truce, predator and prey drink side by side at the shrinking river, too weak and thirsty to fight. Shere Khan lounges nearby, watching Mowgli among the deer and buffalo with open hatred.

SHERE KHAN
(mocking)
Since when do the Free People suffer a manling among them at the Peace Rock?

MOWGLI
(unflinching)
Since the Man-cub was bought for the Pack at a fair price, lame one. Look away from me, Shere Khan, or I will make the Red Flower dance upon your hide.

Shere Khan slinks off, humiliated but patient.

CUT TO:

INT. WOLF DEN - NIGHT (LATER)

Akela, old now, has missed a kill and stands to be challenged for leadership. Several wolves, long swayed by Shere Khan, turn against him and, by extension, against Mowgli.

AKELA
(to Mowgli, urgent, low)
Go, Little Brother. Go to the village of men -- tonight. It is no longer safe for you here.

MOWGLI
(stricken)
The jungle is shut to me, then? I will go -- but I will come back, and I will bring the Red Flower, and you will see who is Pack and who is not.

CUT TO:

EXT. JUNGLE - CATTLE RAVINE - DAY (LATER)

Mowgli, having lived briefly among men and learned to herd cattle, lures Shere Khan into a rocky ravine using a split herd of buffalo as living instruments of the Law.

MOWGLI
(shouting, driving the herd)
Rama! Bring them round -- now, NOW!

The buffalo herd THUNDERS through the ravine, trampling Shere Khan beneath their hooves before he can escape.

Mowgli climbs down and begins skinning the tiger's hide with grim, quiet purpose -- a debt paid at last.

CUT TO:

EXT. COUNCIL ROCK - NIGHT (LATER)

Mowgli returns, dragging Shere Khan's hide before the Pack -- including the wolves who turned against Akela.

MOWGLI
(hard, commanding)
Look well, wolves. Have I kept my word?

The Pack, ashamed, bows low. Akela, restored to honor, watches with quiet pride.

AKELA
(softly)
Hunt well, Man-cub who is our brother. The jungle is yours, whichever way you choose to walk it.

Mowgli looks between the Pack, Baloo, and Bagheera -- and out, for the first time, toward the distant lights of the man-village.

BAGHEERA
(gently)
You cannot stay cub forever, Little Brother. Even the Law bends to that.

MOWGLI
(quiet, resolved)
Then I will walk between both, Bagheera -- as long as the jungle will let me.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
